                           
                            EPHINT 

 Purpose

 read the ephemeris, clock and other files from IGS center, then interpolate
 the orbit, clock, Satellite Phase Center Offsets(PCVs) and other corrections
 according to the given time, expressed by year and day of year.

 needs:
 (1)  The year of interest (2-digit or 4-digit will do)
 (2)  The day of year of interest (Julian day, 0-365/366)
 (3)  The interval you want to interpolate the data
 (4)  An input SP3 file or multiple SP3 files 
 (5)  An input CLK file or multiple clk files 
 (6)  antex file defined by the IGS 

 Usage:

 > ephint -y<year> -j<DOY> -i<interval> -e<SP3File> -c<CLKFile> -x<ATXFile> [-s<PRN>]
 -y : year (2-digit or 4-digit)
 -j : day of year (0-365|366)
 -i : interpolation inteval you needed
 -e : Where to get the ephemeris data with SP3 format. Repeat for multiple files
 -c : Where to get the precise clock data with SP3 format. Repeat for multiple files
 -x : GPS antex file, which can be obtained from IGS analysis center.
 -s : only print out the given PRN's information, optional (to be supported)

 EXAMPLE:

 > ephint -y2011 -j283 -i10 -ecod16570.eph -ecod16571.eph -ecod16572.eph -ccod16571.clk -xigs08_1648.atx > ephint.log &

